<i>Piculus auricularis</i> (Salvin &amp; Godman, 1889)
The <b>Grey-crowned Woodpecker</b> (<i>Colaptes auricularis</i>) is a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird" title="Bird">bird</a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Species" title="Species">species</a> in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woodpecker" title="Woodpecker">woodpecker</a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Family_(biology)" title="Family (biology)">family</a> (Picidae). It was formerly placed in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genus" title="Genus">genus</a> <i>Piculus</i> (Benz <i>et al.</i>, 2006). The <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_name" title="Scientific name" class="mw-redirect">scientific name</a> <i>auricularis</i> means "eared", an appearance created by the confluent, fine patterning of the species' head.
It is <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endemism" title="Endemism">endemic</a> to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a>. Its natural <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitat" title="Habitat">habitat</a> is subtropical or tropical moist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montane_forest" title="Montane forest" class="mw-redirect">montane forests</a>.
